{"/service/ndnp/mthi/batch_mthi_kelseya_ver02/data/sn84036008/00212476596/1908052901/0341.xml":{"full_text":"riette WWtl.', g C\"pny u bil hm.e\nTUESDAYS AND FRIDAYS.\nSubssriplln Rales\nOne Year, in avance............3.01\n1s1 month.............. ....LIi\nntered at the Billings, Ppstomee as\nsecond Class Matter.\nFriday, May 29, 1908.\nSHOULD MAKE A PROTEST.\nFrom reliable sources The Gazette\nlearns that an effort is to be made to\nhave the Northern Pacific Railroad\ncompany change the time of depart\nure for trains from Billings to Red\nLodge and, towns in the Clarke's Fork\nvalley to 7 o'clock instead of 10:30 in\nthe morning as at present. Such a\nchange has been ordered for Sunday\ntrains.\nIf the new schedule is extended to\nweek day traips, people from the\nRed Lodge and Clarke's Forg territory\nwill have to spend an extra day in\nBillings, if they come here to shop.\nAs ,there are scores of persons resid\n~ng in those sections, who purchase\ntheir supplies in Billings the change\nwould work a hardship. It would\nprobably result in diverting some\ntrade from Billings merchants.\nThe chamiber of commerce and the\n\"25,000 club,\" which hold a joint\nmeeting tonight, would do well to ap\npoint a committee to investigate the\nintentions of the railroad company\nand to protest. against any such\nchange in the time of departure of\ntrains during the week.\nn\nBASEBALL IN BIbLINGS.\nBecause the membership of the\nteaihs in the Billings Baseball league\nis made up of local young men,\namateur players, many people who\nhave not seen them play have natural\nly believed that they were giving the\npeople of Billings an inferior class of\nthe national game. Such is not\nthe case. The Billings. Baseball\nleague is furnishing as good exhibi\ntions of the national game as can be\nseen under the auspices of any of the\nminor leagues in the west.\nComparison between the local ama\nteur teams and the professional teams\nin other cities can be made as a re\nsult of the recent visit of the Coun\ntry Club team to Bozeman, where\nthere is a professional nine, composed\nof some of the best known players in\nthe country. Though they were in a\nh~gher altitude and, had not had suf\nflcient practice to acquire the proper\namount of team Work, the Country\nClub team, which is sesond in the\nleague, was able to play Bozeman 7\"\nto 4.\nThere are two other teams in Bill\nings in the same class as the Country\nClub team, so it can be seen that Bill\nings is being given an excellent qual\nity of baseball by the. city league.\n-------o---\nOBSERVE MEMORIAL DAY.\nIt is to be hoped that there Will be\na general observance of Memorial\nday in .Billings Saturday. The largest\nstores of the city, Yegou Bros., Kell\nBros. and Hart-Albin, have agreed to\nclose throughout the day, and many\nof the other mercantila establish\nments have 'signified their intent4on\nof doing likewise. Tire patriotism of\nthose who have so decided is certain\nly to be commended. ?t is to be hoped\nthat every business house in Billings\nwill close. The veterans of both the\nCivil and Spanish-American wars\nhave made arrangements .for an elab\norate program. There will be a pa\nrade and speaking in the afternoon,\nwhile in the morning the graves of\nthe dead veterans will be strewn\nwith flowers. It is well that we take\nat least one day a year to pay tribute\nto the memory of those who have\nfought and died that our country\nmight remain intact. Memorial day\nis set aside as such a day and patriot\nism urges that we observe it.\nThe merchants of Billings in decid\ning to close their places of business\nand observe the day display the\nproper patriotic feeling. It is to be\nhoped that our citizens will do their\npurchasing Friday that the day may\nbe observed without hardship to any\none.\nO\nFEEDING BEET PULP.\nThe success, which has attended\nthe experiments of the Billings Sugar\ncompany in feeding the pulp of sugar\nbeets after the sugar has been ex\ntracted to cattle for fattening pur\nposes, should induce farmers of the\nYellowstone valley to adopt beet pulp\nasl one of the chief rations for topping\nicattle and sheep. In Colorado and\nections ,of the west, where the sugar\niiee ::industry is older than in the\nlo ne valley, the feeding of\npiip ,i vestock is an important in\n.s:. tr. It ils certain to become so\nlfaa eal mixed with beet pulp\n_ an eaellent ration upon which\nStaock,. ,The Billings Sugar\n4 feedin a large\nsheep at. their\noa thisration dur\n't \u00fd \u00b0jajt Mon\n477vastock\nthe yards and ,orougt excellent\nprices\nWith the' establishment of the pro\nposed alifalifa miil in the YellowstoneE\nvalley an'id\" the increase in products I\nif the Billinge sugar factory, the t\nfarmers of the Yellowstone vailey will\nhave an, excellent ration for fatten\ning stock 'and will be able to secure t\nit to fatten their -animale at the time r\nof year, when prices are the best.\nAn alfalfa mill and the' Billings a\nsugar factory will do mnore than any\nthing else to make this country 'a\nproducer of fatted cattle. When the\nSouth Omaha delegation to the live- I\nstock conventions of the west. was in\nBillings, the spokesman asserted that\nthe visit here was to become acquaint. 0\ned with a section that South Omaha\ncommission men believed would soon\nbe sending large shipments of fatted\nstock to market. The success of the\nsugar company's experiment shows\nthe wisdom of the South Omahans.\nBillings is excellently situated to be\ncome a cattle feeding center and her\nalfalfa and sugar beet pulp offer the u\nproper feed.\no v\n\"NEAR BEER\" INDUSTRY. s\nA new industry has beep started in d\nGeorgia as a result of the, enforce\nment of the prohibition laws. It is\" p\nthe manufacture of \"near beer,\" an si\nimitation of the foaming lager, yet ci\ncontaining less than one per cent al- u'\ncohol. It is proving profitable for the N\nbreweries, which were forced to cease tt\nthe manufacture of the genuine arti\ncle the first of January.\nUnder the United States revenue n\nlaws the dispenser of \"near beer\" is n\ncompelled to take out a liquor license b\nand, so popular is the new beverage h\nthat the liquor licenses issued in\nGeorgia have doubled in number since\nthe prohibition law became effective.\nIt is freely predicted in Georgia news\npapers that the number of licenses\nwill be quadrupled before, next Jan\nuary.\n\"Near beer\" is an ideal temperance c\nbeverage in that no person could con\nsume sufficient of it to become intox\nicated,. As a result, not only the \"near\nbeer\" saloons, but the soda fountains, a\ndrug stores and' country merchants b\nhave taken out licenses to dispense h\n\"near beer.\"\nReports show that the Georgia\nbreweries are turning out more of e:\nthe \"near beer\" this year than they r\ndid of real beer, and the profit, both o\nfor the brewer and the retailer, is\nlarger than is the 'case with the real\narticle.\nWhile some of the Anti-Saloon\nleague workers are anxious to sup\npress the manufacture of \"near beer,\" a\nthere are others who believe that it\nsupplies a satisfactory solution of the\nliquor question, providing a beverage\nthat satisfies the appetite of the con\nfirmed beer drinker without produc a\ning intoxication. n\nGeorgia seems to have- successfully i\nproduced a drink that may be profits h\nbly manufactured in breweries and\nsold in prohibition states, and so the\nopposition of the brewers to the 'ad- h\nvance of the prohibition wave should\nbe reduced. Now if someone will'\nonly invent \"near whiskey,\" a \"near\ngin\" and a \"near wine\" there would\nprobably be' little opposition left to\nthe anti-liquor advocates.\nBUSINESS OUTLOOK IMPROVED.\nThe financial papers throughout\nthe country are taking a most op\ntimistic view of the business outlook. si\nEverywhere the impression seems to\nbe that there will be a' gradual i-a tc\nprovement in the business situation,\nculminating in a decided business re\nvival in the fall. The situation at\nthe end 'of last week is well stated l\nin the following from an eastern trade w\npaper: g'\n\"The indications of better. business t\nare most widely distributed through c]\nthe wholesale and lobbing branches. I\nIn cotton goods there Was a notice- c\nably larger demand, and in some b\ncases a tendency to higher prices. f\nMore orders are reported in woolen' t\ngoods, the movement being stronger T\nthan for some weeks; while footwear v\norders are better, though still small h\nby comparison with former years. The s1\nreports of improyement are most de -c\ncided from the southwest and the h\nnorthwest, the southern and eastern\ntrade being still restricted. ti\n\"In iron and steel enlarged transac-'p\ntions and what seems to be the most\nvigorous demand from consuming In- o\nterests since the reaction of last fall\nare very clearly based on the convic-'t\ntion that pig iron is down to the hard\npan basis. I\n\"A turn in the accumulation of\nmoney in New York is' indicated by bi\nthe bank statement of yesterday. The\nloss of a little under $3,000,000 in\ncash is small compared with the ex\nport of about $10,000,000 in gold. But\nan expansion of nearly $18,000,000 in\nloans results in reducing the surplus\nreserve $8,121,000. As this still leaves\nthe plethoric excess above legal re\nquirements of $56,485,000 the change t\nis more favorable than otherwise.\nClearing house exchanges for the H\nwhole country show an enlargement.\" 'Si\nSPREAD OF PROHIBITION. vi\nIndicatlons are that North Carolina ti\nhas joined the ranks of prohibition r\nstates. If the first returns from the pt\nelection of yesterday prove correct\nthe state will eliminate the liquor i\nbusiness January 1, 1909. t\nThe spread of the prohibition sen- ta\ntiment has been remarkable. Maine\nbegan the movement in 1855;, Kansas\nwent dry in 1880 and North Dakota\nin 1889. Oklahoma was admitted to of\nthe union as a temperance state and q\nGeorgia swelled the ranks of prohi\nbition states January. 1: of this year\nWith the addition of North Carolina\nAlabama' and Mississippi January 1\n1909, eight states of the union will\nhave eliminated the liquor trafic.\nIn addition to the eight totally\n\"dry\" states, present and prospective\nthere are in other commonwealthe\nnearly 1,300 counties, almost 10,00(\ntowns and townships and 136 cities\nwith populations,aranging up. to 150,\n000., which have been made \"dry'\" by\n'ocal option elections.\nThere are 11 cities, each having a\npopulation of more than 50,000. that\nare \"dry,\" and 19 whose population\nis' between 20,000 and 50,000. Many\nof the states have been sw rt close\nt,, rohibitory laws by the spread of\nlocal option sentiment; one-half of\nNebraska is without saloons; of the\n241 counties in Texas 152 ate \"dry;\"\n29 6f the 55 counties in West Virginia\nhave sout out the saloons; 66 of the\n100 counties of Virginia have adopted\nlocal option; 74 of the 115 counties of\nMissouri are in the local option col.\numn; in Ohio three counties and\n1,621 townships and small towns have\nvoted against liquor, while in Minne\nsota 1,611 townships and villages are\ndry.\nThe recent election in Illinois\nplaced a large part of the \"Sucker\"\nstate in the \"dry\" 'olumn. In Massa\nchusetts 76 per cent of the state is\nunder prohibitory law; 75 per cent of\nMinnesota is \"dry,\" while in Ken\ntucky but four counties are wholly\n\"wet.\"\nIn the face of such statistics it is\nno wonder that the liquor dealers and\nmanufacturers of the nation have\nbeen organizing to combat the pro\nhibition wave.\n-------o------\nPRESERVE THE PARKS.\nIt is unfortunate indeed that a few\nof the local business men are so short\nsighted that they oppose th'e efforts\nof the boosters for a more beautiful\nBillings to persuade the Northern Pa\ncific Railroad company to iermit the\nretention of the land around the\npresent depot as a public park, when\nthe new depot is 'ereoted. But be\ncause of this opposition the Billings\nboosters will have to work that much\nharder in their efforts to save to the\ncity the only park it now possesses.\nThe few men, who are opposing the\nefforts to save this park, do not rep\nresent the sentiment of the citizens\nof Billings at large. Hundreds of peo\nple have expressed themselves upon\nthe subject since the agitation com.\nmenced and save these few, who\nwere active last night, at the joint\nmeeting of the chamber of commerce\nand the \"25,000 club\" in the city hall\nin speaking against trying to persuade\nthe railroad company to permit the\npark to remain, all are anxious that\nthe railroad company take action\nagainst leasing the land. The frater\nnal organizations, that have discussed\nit; the labor unions, whose members\nhave discussed it; the membership of\nthe chamber of commerce and the\n\"25,000 club\" and the Woman's club\nhave gone on record as wanting the\npark preserved. When the question\nof postponing action temporarily was\nvoted upon last night, only a small\nper cenit of'those in attendance at the\nmeeting voted, showing that the ma\njority were not actually with the op\nponents of the park.\nThere is nodoubt what the railroad\ncompany will do. It will take what\never action the people of Billings de\nsire.\nIt has been urged that the land is\ntoo valuable to maintain as a public\npark. There is no use to which it\ncould be placed that would prove\nmore valuable to the citizens of Bill\nings. It has been said that the land\nwas needed for business sites. A\nglance at the business sections of Bill\nings, shows the fallacy of such a\nclaim. There are scores of vacant\nbusiness lots, in every bit as good lo\ncations as the park, available for\nbuilding purposes and it is a notable\nfact that the price of business proper\nty in Billings is comparatively low.\nThe one thing for which the land is\nvaluable outside a park is for ware\nhouse purposes and if it is leased out\nside of the first floor any buildings\nconstructed would be used as ware\nhouses. The people of Billings do not\nwant warehouses in the principal por\ntion of the city. Thegnen, who own\n'roperty on the northern side of Mon\ntana avenue do not want warehouses\non the other side.\nThe construction of warehouses on\nthe southern side of Montana avenue\nalong the track would reduce the\nvalue of property on the northern\nside for it would mean the removal of\nbusiness from Montana avenu4 to\nstreets farther from the railroad\ntracks. The experience of other cities\nin this respect should be a warning to\nthe people. of Billings and should' ;tmJ,\nulate the agitation to have the' land\nmaintained as a park.\nSome of the few who favor permitting\nthe railroad company to lease the lald\nsay we must not oppose the wishes of\nthe railroad colipany. What 'rot. Did\nnot President Elliott, Vice Presldent\nHannaford, General Manager Slade,\nSuperintendent Goodell 'and other of\nficials of the company, on their recent\nvisits to Billings declare, that it was\nthe wish of the oflclals of the r4il\nroad conmpany \"to fin4 out what the\npeople of 'Billings want?\" It is but in\ncompliance with their expressed de\nsire that the people of Billings assert\nthat they want a public park main\ntained on Montana avenue.\nBillings needs a public park. She\n-eeds it along the railroad right of\nway that the hundreds of thousands\n3f people who pass through here an\nnually may see what manner of city\n\"Billing, is., Warehouses or cheap\nbusiness blocks such as would have td\nbe erec ed on the leases giveni by.the\n,railtoad company would obstruct the\nView.\nIt is said that certain people :have\n\"i formed the railroad company\nthat Billings is willing to have: the\nparks -removed and the land leased.\nISuch information was wrong. It was\nnot In, accord with the sentiment of\nthe people of ,Billings. It has takein\n,25 years to secure the green grass and\ntall trees that complose the ,park and\n-it would be a shame to permit their\n-removal without a protest. If the\nsentiment of the citizens is properly\nspresepted to the railroad e6mpany the\n,result- will be that the officials of the\n(Northern Pacific will agree to the\nm'aintenance of the park. It is the\none thing for which the land is really\nfitted. It is what the people of 'Bill\n'ings want. It is what, until the pres\nent time, the railroad company has\nIbeen anxious to maintain. There\n,should be united effort on the part of\nIthe citizens to persuade the railroad\ncompany, in a friendly manner, 'to\ngrant the use of the land for. a public\nspark,\nReports from New York are to the\neffect that gold is going out of the\nUnited States in almost as large quan\ntities as it was imported during the so\ncalled Panic of last fall.' There could\nnot be better evidence that the cur\nrency stringency has completely pass\ned and that times should be as good\nas before the panic.\n--o---\nThe Gazette has received the first\nPopy of \"The Treasure State,\" a\nweekly -newspaper published in Hel\nena by John H. Raftery, recently, edi\ntor of the Independent. The first\nnumber is an excellent publication.\nMr. Raftery has spent a life of service\nin newspaper work and the newspaper\nShould consequently prove, a success.\n\nThe stories which some large east\nern papers have been printing about\nthe enormous losses of sheep 'and\ncattle in a recent snowstorm in the\nYellowstone valley will be news to\nour sheep and cattle owners.\n-0-----\nCongressmen will soon cease their\ntalking in Washington to resume talk\ning to their constitue-ts. Some of\nthem will have to talk pretty hard,\ntoo, to have the privilege of again\ntalking in Washington.\n~-0-\nE]verybody seems to want enforced\npublicity of campaign contributions\nexcept certain congressmen. The\ncongressmen may think that their in\nactvity will give them sufficient\npublicity.\n---o--\nThe question, that most perplexes\nthe Montana democrats is whether\nthey can b,e, at the barrel more suc\ncessfully ,with a gubernatorial 'nom\nination than with a vice presidential\nendorsement.\n0--\nThe democratic statesmen are talk\ning about nominating a winner at the\nDenver convention. Some of those\ndemocratic leaders always were\ndreamers.\n-o-\nCongress intends providing that a\nman with bonds can get emergency\ncurrency. The trouble is those of us\nwho need currency in an emergency\ndon't have the bonds.\n-o-\nThis weather should induce people\nto take out insurance in the home in\nsurance company, the Fraternal Order\nof Mountaineers. It pays losses where\npeople drown.\n----0--\nWhen the reports of the recent\nheavy rains in Montana are printed\nin the east, if the space writers con\ntinue as in the past, look for an awful\ncasualty list.\nThe country may heave a sigh of\nrelief. William J. Bryan has an\nnounced that he will stay at home\nfor a few days and' make no speeches.\nSince Hardin has secured an abun\ndant supply of water she. can offer\ninducements to railroad presidents\nand promoters :to locate there.\n-0-o-\nBillings people who want to be pa\ntriotic can celebrate the Fourth of\nJuly in Joliet or Forsyth. Both will\nhave celebrations.'\n\u00b7o\nRepresentative government in Ru\nsia seems to lead to jail, judging from\nthe number of douma members now\nheld in custody.\n-0\nWeather such as we have been ex\npprlenclng belies thg statement that\neastern Montana Ls a dry land farm\ning dlstrict\nPoltlcs as well as rligion seems to\nengross the attention of delegates to\nthe general conferenhee of the Metho\ndist church.\nSAny one who thought Harry Thaw\nhad an income was mistaken. It is\nproved to be nothing but an incum\nbrance.\nUnder the circumstances Mae Wood\n'should be glad she is not the wife of\nUnited States Senator Plitt,\nSenator Platt is a far Iss intereast\ning figure in the se.iate chamber than\nhe was in a New York court room.\nWhat is needed 'on the Hintley\ntract just now is not irrigation but\ndrainage.\nThe business. of the local land of\nflece is an indication .of the way home\nseekers are flocking 'into eastern\nMontana. Not a day, passes but what\nfrom three to five families file on\nhomesteads. It is said 'that an equal\nnumber purchase farms fromn real es\ntate dealers. Ten new families, 50\npeople added to the population of Yel\nlowstone county daily is the way this\nsection is growing.\n--o-0-\n\"King Edward, Queen Alexandria\n,and President Fallieres proved such\nan attraction at, the opera in London\nWednesday night that some enterpris\ning American theatrical manager will\nprobably. offer them permanent en\ngagements.\n---0--\nCarrie Nation has been sent to the\nworkhouse for disturbance. It is a\ngood place for her. She should be\npermitted to work off, some of her\nsurplus energy. Then- she might not\nbe so anxious to use the hatchet in\nthe future.'\n0-\n,\"Will'ie\" Hearst started off well in\nthe recount of ballots cast in the last\ncity election in New York by gaining\n27 votes. It looks like there was a\npossibility of the name of the mayor'\nof Greater New York bein'g changed.\n\nJohn Mitchell is probably too wise\nto permit any democratic leaders to\npersuade him to engage in a losing\nfight 'by accepting the vice presiden\ntial nomination on the democratic\nticket.\nFour more days and the Merry\nWidow will have to give way to the\nJune bride.\n\nThe Atlanta Constitution has sug\ngested a wise way to find a candidate\nfor the vice presidency. It urges\nmaking the office compulsory, not op\ntional.\n---0--\nIf this, weather continues Dr. Sud\nduth will have to find some other lo\ncality to promote dry' land farming.\nAutomobile owners could profitably\nremove the engines from their cars\nand place them in launches.\n-0--\nSTATE PRESS COMMENT.\nBoost the boosters and watch\nLaurel grow.-Laurel Sentinei.\nA federal official in Vermont has\nbeen fred for taking part in politics.\nPerhaps that rule doesn't apply to\nwestern states.-Butte Inter Moun\ntai'.\nBut that Cleveland street car strike\nwill not be taken seriously until it in\nterferes with the baseball attendance.\n-Helena Independent.\nChouteau county mines sent $21,640\nof gold to the Helena assay office\nduring the month of April. That is\nthe largest amount of any county in\nthe state except Fergus county.\nChinook Opinion.\nIf Mark Hanna could have heard\nthe good things that were said of\nhim at thn unveiling of his monument\nSaturday, he would have felt inclined\nto draw a deadly parallel with some\nthings that had been said years ago\n-Missoulian.\nSecretary Taft's political managers,\naccording to the other republican can\ndidates, believe in claiming 'enough\nwhen they 'claim anything, and in\nconsequence they have claimed every\nthing in sight and a good deal that\nis out of sight.-Butte Miner.\nWhen it comes to log rolling and\nwire pulling those Methodist minis\nters. who have been engaged ih se\nlecting bishops could give some of\nthe most adroit politicians and po\nlitical workers a few pointers.-Butte\nMiner.\n\nSome times it's luck to be poor. For\ninstance, there is the Missouri man\nwho would have been one of Mrs.\nGunness' victims had he possessed\nsufmcient cash' to eniable hip to visit\nthe fair but Mlcked Indiana widow.\nRepublican-Picket.\nAccording to recent reports from\nthe lower Yellowstone valley, the\nfarmers of that region have been more\nconcerned of late with the constrau\ntion of ditches to carry the water OFF\ntheir lands -than to 'bring it O~N.\nDawson County Review.\nThere isn't muach, d1ierence 'be\ntween Mr. Bryan and that life-reader\nfellow in Helena. Each makes money\nfor himself by telling others how to\nmake money; but it is. noticeable that\nthe others' do not prosper if they\ntake the advice.-Mimssoulian.\nThe springing of the name of John\nMitchell at this tiine is tsken to iesn\nthat the efforts being put forth by\nrepresentative democrats of the south\nin favor of Mr. Conrad have alarmed\nthose in the east who do not want a\nwestern man on the'tidket with Bryan.\n-Helena Record.\nThere is one spot in Montana where\nthe perennial candidate for the presi\ndency is below par. The Deer Lodge\ncounty democrats in their conven\ntion Ipassed resolutions favoring John\nson of lMinnesota for president. Coh\nrad's name' wasn't mentloned.-Fer\ngus County Argus.\nZi'hose May mnowdrifts In Custer\ncounty- grow deeper, as the story\nspeeds eastward. Starti ig, out, with 22\ninches at, Miles City;, they ibecame\nfour feet at St. Paul and six feet at\nChicago. By the tibie the story\nreaches New York, every log cabin in.\nQCuter county will be buried.-Butte\nInter Mountain.\nCongressman Cole of Ohio has\ntwice secured his nomination as the\nrepublican 'candidate by the flip of a\ncoin .Different here., In Montana sev\neral would-be statesmen have 'ndt\nonly secured their nomination but\nalso their election because they had\nthe coin-and were not' afraid to'\nspend it.-Juliet Journal.\nThe odd talk of John Mitchell to\nmake the race with Bryan is being\nrevived. Mitchell would help the\nticket; it is not likely that the former\nlabor leader would accept the \"l3em\non,\" as he is a pronouncedly enthusi\nastic believer in the Roosevelt poll\ncies, and it is not improbable that\nRoosevelt. has him. slated for more\nsubstantial honors than playing sec\nond fiddle to \"a dead one.\"-Butte\nNews.\nThe dispatchers have it that a New\nJersey justice \"indignantly denies\"\nthat he married De Sagan ano Anna\nGould. It ought to be libel to accuse\nan honest, hard-working, respectable\njustice of a .tning i.ee that.-Butte In\nter Mountain.\n.Montana is a big state, and she\nneeds to be that to accommodate the\nhomeseekers who have learned her\nmerits.-Missoulian.\nMrs. Gunness is coming to life alto\ngether too easily and too frequently.\nBut her victims are sure enough dead.\n-Anaconda Standard.\nMr. Bryan, taking his cue undoubt\nedly from. Mr. Conrad, announces that\nhe wilh look after his home fences for\na while now.-Helena Record.\nThat Johnson boom over in Leer\nLodge county is becoming quite lone\nsome, and, unless.all signs are wrong,\nit will be mightily sorry that it ever\nblossomed forth.-Missqula 'Herald.\nAnd '\"Bill\" Bryan said to \"'Bill\" Taft,\n\"Do you favor the campaign publicity\nbill?\" anau Bill\" 'Taft said to \"Bill\nBryan, \"-res I favor the bill, do you\nfavor the bill, 'Bill'?\" And since both\nBills\". favor ..i one particular bill,\ncongress should surely pass the bill.\nHelena Record,\n\nThe man who can~t go to a theater\nana enjoy the play, as well as per\nmiitting others to do so without get\n:tlng up at the end of each act and\ntramping on the toes of the rest of\nthe row while crowding his way out\nto gd and grab on., ought to fetch a\nbottle or, stay at the saloon.-Boze\nman' Republicane-ourier.\nINTERESTING PACTS.\nSouthern California yields 2,000 tons\nof salt per year.\nAustralia's largest cattle herg is\nthat running on the Victoria river\nstation.\nThe Chinese government intends to\npurchase, immediately, 40 torpedo\nboats and four gunboats.\nFew members of the supreme court\nhave exceeded the time Justice Har\nlan served-30 years.\nMiss Elizabeth K, Jackson of Mo\nbile, Ala., is said to be one of two\nwomen claim clerks in the country.\nOne of the great transatlantic\nsteamship lines has added trained\nnurses to the medical personnel of its\nvessels.\nMiss Hattie Greensfelder of St.\nLouis recently conducted a suit at\nMexico, Mo., for damages for the\ndeath of a child.\nUp to the beginning of December\n918,000 crates of rabbits, totaling\namnout 22,000 tons, had been received\nin London during 1907.\nMiss Mabel T. Boardman of Wash\nInajton is now making a tour of the\nwest, trying to arouse interest in the\nRed Cross organization.\nSeven former students of the Chi\ncago Training school are among the\nmissionarleg appointed by the Bengal\nMethodist conference for 1908.\nJoseph,Pulitzer is tle latest Amer\nican Qtf means to buy .a fine steam\nyacht abroad. IAis ,1600ton'cruiseer\nwas launch